      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">1. Not Comparing Bond vs Donation Options</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            The bond option returns your $300,000 after 5 years, making net cost ~$80,000. But you lose 5 years of
            investment returns on that capital. Calculate your opportunity cost based on your expected investment
            returns. If you'd earn more than 5-6% annually, donation might be better. If you prefer capital
            preservation, bonds win.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">2. Incomplete Source of Funds Documentation</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            The most common cause of delays. You must prove every dollar of your investment came from legitimate
            sources. Employment contracts, business records, sale agreements, inheritance documentation—maintain
            a clear paper trail. "I have the money" isn't sufficient proof.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">3. Using Unlicensed Agents</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            Only licensed agents can submit applications. Working with unlicensed intermediaries risks fraud and
            rejected applications. Verify agent licensing with the Citizenship by Investment Board. Licensed agents
            have direct government relationships and understand current requirements.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">4. Skipping Evacuation Coverage</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            St. Lucia's healthcare is basic—adequate for minor issues but limited for complex care. If you visit
            the island, ensure your insurance includes air ambulance evacuation to Martinique, Barbados, or Miami.
            Without coverage, evacuation costs $15,000-$40,000+.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">5. Assuming St. Lucia Has US E-2 Treaty</h4>
          <p class="text-red-900 text-sm mt-1">
            St. Lucia does NOT have an E-2 Treaty with the United States. If US residence via E-2 investor visa
            is your goal, Grenada is the only Caribbean CBI option. Don't assume all Caribbean programs offer
            the same benefits—research treaty access carefully.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

