    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the government bond option work?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            You purchase $300,000+ in non-interest-bearing St. Lucian government bonds. The bonds are held for 5 years,
            after which your principal is returned in full. You also pay a non-refundable $50,000 administrative fee
            plus standard due diligence costs. Net cost is ~$80,000 (fees only), making it potentially cheaper than
            donation—but you sacrifice 5 years of investment returns on your capital.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to live in St. Lucia?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            No. St. Lucia has zero residency requirement—you never need to visit the island to obtain or maintain
            citizenship. This is more flexible than Antigua (5 days in 5 years) and equal to Dominica (no requirement).
            You can hold the passport purely for travel benefits while living anywhere in the world.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I include adult children?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, dependent children up to age 25 can be included. Children 26-30 can also be included if they're
            enrolled in full-time education and financially dependent. Each additional dependent adds $25,000 (NEF)
            or corresponding fees for other options. Adult children over 30 cannot be included.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does St. Lucia have a tax treaty with my country?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            St. Lucia has limited tax treaties—primarily with the UK and CARICOM countries. There's no personal income
            tax on foreign-source income for non-residents. Capital gains, inheritance, and wealth taxes don't exist.
            However, CBI citizenship alone doesn't change your tax residency. Consult a tax professional about your
            specific situation and home country obligations.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does St. Lucia compare to other Caribbean CBI?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            St. Lucia sits in the middle tier: more expensive than Dominica but with unique bond option; fewer visa-free
            countries than St. Kitts (157) but zero residency requirement; no US E-2 Treaty (unlike Grenada). Key
            differentiator is the refundable bond option for capital preservation. Best for applicants who want the
            bond option or value zero residency requirement.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I add dependents later?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, you can add dependents after citizenship is granted. Newborn children are added easily; new spouses
            or other dependents require a separate application with additional fees. Adding family members later
            typically costs more than including them initially, so include everyone eligible from the start if possible.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          St. Lucia's CBI program stands out for its government bond option—unique among Caribbean programs. If you
          have $300,000+ available and prefer capital preservation, the bond option returns your principal after
          5 years, making net cost ~$80,000. This appeals to conservative investors who don't want to "lose" the
          donation amount.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          The zero residency requirement is another key differentiator—you never need to visit St. Lucia. Combined
          with 145+ visa-free countries (UK, Schengen, Hong Kong, Singapore), it's a solid choice for travel freedom.
          The main gaps: no US E-2 Treaty access (Grenada is better for US aspirations) and family of 4+ pricing
          that's higher than Antigua.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900">
          Healthcare on the island is basic—adequate for routine care but requiring evacuation for complex procedures.
